data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 with no migration needed.

That said, the code could be modernized to use `Task`/`Parallel` for better resource usage:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This uses the thread pool instead of creating one thread per item, but it's an improvement — not a required migration step.
